  "is_vocab": false,
  "stimulus_html": "<p>The antitumor antibiotic mitomycin C functions by forming cross-links in DNA chains.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBaVVaIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--918dd1af1d0729201fa0dd155d0b6ebdee74de84/OChem_24_EC_026.jpg\" alt=\"The removal of methanol from mitomycin C forms enamine. This reacts with two amine groups connected to deoxyribonucleic acid to form an intermediate. This reacts to form the final product.\">",
  "questions": [
    {
      "id": 361653,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "The first step is loss of methoxide and formation of an iminium ion intermediate that is deprotonated to give an enamine. Show the mechanism.",
      "answers": [],
      "hints": [],
      "formats": [
        "free-response"
      ],
      "combo_choices": []
    },
    {
      "id": 361654,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "The second step is reaction of the enamine with DNA to open the three-membered, nitrogen-containing (aziridine) ring. Show the mechanism.",
      "answers": [],
      "hints": [],
      "formats": [
        "free-response"
      ],
      "combo_choices": []
    },
    {
      "id": 361655,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "The third step is loss of carbamate (NH<sub>2</sub>CO<sub>2</sub><sup>–</sup>) and formation of an unsaturated iminium ion, followed by a conjugate addition of another part of the DNA chain. Show the mechanism.",
